Arrays 

Introduction

An Array is a linear data structure that stores elements of the same data type in contiguous memory locations.
Elements are accessed using an index, starting from 0.

Array Representation in Memory

Arrays are stored in continuous memory locations.
The address of an element is calculated using:
Address = Base Address + (Index × Size of Data Type)
This enables constant-time (O(1)) random access.

Array Traversal

Traversal means visiting each element of the array one by one.
Used to display, process, or update array elements.
Time Complexity: O(n)

Searching in Arrays

1. Linear Search
Checks each element sequentially.
Works on both sorted and unsorted arrays.
Time Complexity: O(n)

2. Binary Search
Works only on sorted arrays.
Repeatedly divides the search space into halves.
Time Complexity: O(log n)

Measuring Time Complexity

Accessing an element: O(1)
Traversing an array: O(n)
Searching (Linear): O(n)
Searching (Binary): O(log n) (sorted arrays only)
Insertion/Deletion: O(n) (due to shifting of elements)

When to Use Arrays

When the number of elements is fixed or known in advance.
When fast random access to elements is required.
When memory efficiency is important.
Suitable for storing homogeneous data like marks, salaries, temperatures, etc.

Advantages

Fast access using index (O(1)).
Simple to implement.
Efficient memory usage due to contiguous storage.

Disadvantages

Fixed size (cannot grow dynamically).
Insertion and deletion are costly (O(n)).
Can lead to memory wastage or overflow if size is not chosen properly.